"Petoukhov V., Semenov V.A.","A link between reduced Barents-Kara sea ice and cold winter extremes over northern continents",2010,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","115","21", D21111,"","",,,10.1029/2009JD013568,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78249289140&partnerID=40&md5=6c16d93c0a335d7474bfd49aa370996f","Potsdam-Institute for Climate Impact Research, Telegrafenberg A62, PO Box 60 12 03, D-14473/14412 Potsdam, Germany; Leibniz Institute of Marine Sciences, University of Kiel, Duesternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany; A.M. Obukhov Institute of Atmospheric Physics RAS, Moscow, Russian Federation","Petoukhov, V., Potsdam-Institute for Climate Impact Research, Telegrafenberg A62, PO Box 60 12 03, D-14473/14412 Potsdam, Germany; Semenov, V.A., Leibniz Institute of Marine Sciences, University of Kiel, Duesternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany, A.M. Obukhov Institute of Atmospheric Physics RAS, Moscow, Russian Federation","The recent overall Northern Hemisphere warming was accompanied by several severe northern continental winters, as for example, extremely cold winter 2005-2006 in Europe and northern Asia. Here we show that anomalous decrease of wintertime sea ice concentration in the Barents-Kara (B-K) seas could bring about extreme cold events like winter 2005-2006. Our simulations with the ECHAM5 general circulation model demonstrate that lower-troposphere heating over the B-K seas in the Eastern Arctic caused by the sea ice reduction may result in strong anticyclonic anomaly over the Polar Ocean and anomalous easterly advection over northern continents. This causes a continental-scale winter cooling reaching -1.5°C, with more than 3 times increased probability of cold winter extremes over large areas including Europe. Our results imply that several recent severe winters do not conflict the global warming picture but rather supplement it, being in qualitative agreement with the simulated large-scale atmospheric circulation realignment. Furthermore, our results suggest that high-latitude atmospheric circulation response to the B-K sea ice decrease is highly nonlinear and characterized by transition from anomalous cyclonic circulation to anticyclonic one and then back again to cyclonic type of circulation as the B-K sea ice concentration gradually reduces from 100% to ice free conditions. We present a conceptual model that may explain the nonlinear local atmospheric response in the B-K seas region by counter play between convection over the surface heat source and baroclinic effect due to modified temperature gradients in the vicinity of the heating area. Copyright © 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Arctic engineering; Climatology; Computer simulation; Global warming; Heating; Sea ice; Anticyclonic anomalies; Atmospheric circulation; Atmospheric response; Baroclinic effects; Cold winter; Conceptual model; Cyclonic circulation; Cyclonic types; Eastern Arctic; General circulation model; Heat sources; Highly nonlinear; Ice-free conditions; Kara Sea; Northern Hemispheres; Sea ice concentration; Temperature gradient; Winter cooling; Oceanography; advection; atmospheric circulation; general circulation model; global warming; heat source; Northern Hemisphere; sea ice; troposphere; winter; Arctic Ocean; Barents Sea; Europe; Kara Sea",,,,,,"Alexander, M.A., Bhatt, U.S., Walsh, J.E., Timlin, M.S., Miller, J.S., Scott, J.D., The atmospheric response to realistic Arctic sea ice anomalies in an AGCM during winter (2004) J. Clim., 17, pp. 890-905; Bengtsson, L., Semenov, V.A., Johannessen, O.M., The early twentieth-century warming in the Arctic-A possible mechanism (2004) J. Clim., 17, pp. 4045-4057; Baldwin, M.P., Dunkerton, T.J., Stratospheric harbingers of anomalous weather regimes (2001) Science, 294, pp. 581-584; Brönnimann, S., Luterbacher, J., Staehelin, J., Svendby, T.M., Hansen, G., Svenøe, T., Extreme climate of the global troposphere and stratosphere 1940-1942 related to El Niño (200